<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>quaternion</b> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Number_system" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Number system">nu=
mber system</a> extends the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comple=
x_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex numbers</a>. Quaternions were fi=
rst described by the Irish mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/William_Rowan_Hamilton" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton">William Row=
an Hamilton</a> in 1843<sup id=3D"cite_ref-letter1843_1-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-letter184=
3-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and applied to <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanics" title=3D"Mechanics">mech=
anics</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_spa=
ce" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dimensional space</a>. The set =
of all quaternions is conventionally denoted by <span class=3D"mwe-math-ele=
ment mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-mat=
h-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/19=
98/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \ \mathbb {H} \ }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">H</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mtext>&nbsp;</mtext>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \ \mathbb {H}=
 \ }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3a769054089d056b14172d7c770260f441ee0023" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.969ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ \=
mathbb {H} \ }"></span> ('H' for <i>Hamilton</i>) or by <span class=3D"nowr=
ap">
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>H</b></span>.</span> Quaternions are not quite a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"Fie=
ld (mathematics)"><i>field</i></a> because, in general, multiplication of q=
uaternions is not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Commutative">commutative</a>. Quaternions provi=
de a definition of the quotient of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Vector_(mathematics_and_physics)" title=3D"Vector (mathematics and phy=
sics)">vectors</a> in a three-dimensional space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_no=
