ion" title=3D"Quaternions and spatial rotation">calculations involving thre=
e-dimensional rotations</a>, such as in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/3D_computer_graphics" title=3D"3D computer graphics">three-dimensiona=
l computer graphics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_=
vision" title=3D"Computer vision">computer vision</a>, robotics, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_resonance_imaging" title=3D"Magneti=
c resonance imaging">magnetic resonance imaging</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mamo=
ne_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quater=
nion#cite_note-Mamone-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Texture_(crystalline)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Texture (cryst=
alline)">crystallographic texture</a> analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lunze_7-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#=
cite_note-Lunze-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> They can be used alongside other methods of r=
otation, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_angles" tit=
le=3D"Euler angles">Euler angles</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Rotation_matrix" title=3D"Rotation matrix">rotation matrices</a>, or=
 as an alternative to them, depending on the application.
</p><p>In modern terms, quaternions form a four-dimensional <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_algebra" title=3D"Associative algebra=
">associative</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_alge=
bra" title=3D"Composition algebra">normed</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Division_algebra" title=3D"Division algebra">division algebra</=
a> over the real numbers, and therefore a ring, also a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_ring" title=3D"Division ring">division ring</=
a> and a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(ring_theory)" tit=
le=3D"Domain (ring theory)">domain</a>. It is a special case of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_algebra" title=3D"Clifford algeb=
ra">Clifford algebra</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classifi=
cation_of_Clifford_algebras" title=3D"Classification of Clifford algebras">=
classified</a> as <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
