<p>Quaternions were introduced by Hamilton in 1843.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SeeH=
azewinkel_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Quaternion#cite_note-SeeHazewinkel-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Important precursors to t=
his work included <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_four-s=
quare_identity" title=3D"Euler's four-square identity">Euler's four-square =
identity</a> (1748) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olinde_Rod=
rigues" title=3D"Olinde Rodrigues">Olinde Rodrigues</a>' <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%E2%80%93Rodrigues_parameters" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Euler=E2=80=93Rodrigues parameters">parameterization of gene=
ral rotations by four parameters</a> (1840), but neither of these writers t=
reated the four-parameter rotations as an algebra.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite=
_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bradley-Sandifer-2007_11-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_not=
e-Bradley-Sandifer-2007-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-12"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" ti=
tle=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Gauss</a> had discovered quaternions in 1819, =
but this work was not published until 1900.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-1=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Hamilton knew that the complex numbers could be interpreted as <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(geometry)" title=3D"Point (geome=
try)">points</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(mathe=
matics)" title=3D"Plane (mathematics)">plane</a>, and he was looking for a =
way to do the same for points in three-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Space" title=3D"Space">space</a>. Points in space can be r=
epresented by their coordinates, which are triples of numbers, and for many=
 years he had known how to add and subtract triples of numbers. However, fo=
r a long time, he had been stuck on the problem of multiplication and divis=
ion. He could not figure out how to calculate the quotient of the coordinat=
es of two points in space. In fact, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ferdinand_Georg_Frobenius" title=3D"Ferdinand Georg Frobenius">Ferdinand =
Georg Frobenius</a> later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frobeniu=
s_theorem_(real_division_algebras)" title=3D"Frobenius theorem (real divisi=
on algebras)">proved</a> in 1877 that for a division algebra over the real =
numbers to be finite-dimensional and associative, it cannot be three-dimens=
ional, and there are only three such division algebras: <span class=3D"mwe-=
math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline=
 mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w=
3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbb {R,C} }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
