=3D-1}"></span>
</p><p>Although the carving has since faded away, there has been an annual =
pilgrimage since 1989, called the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Hamilton_Walk" title=3D"Hamilton Walk">Hamilton Walk</a></i>, for scient=
ists and mathematicians who process from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Dunsink_Observatory" title=3D"Dunsink Observatory">Dunsink Obser=
vatory</a> to the Royal Canal bridge in remembrance of Hamilton's discovery=
.
</p><p>On the following day, Hamilton wrote a letter to his friend and fell=
ow mathematician, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_T._Graves" =
title=3D"John T. Graves">J.T. Graves</a>, describing the train of thought t=
hat led to his discovery. The letter was later published in a letter to the=
 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophical_Magazine" title=
=3D"Philosophical Magazine">Philosophical Magazine</a></i>;<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-letter1843_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-letter1843-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hamilton states:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>And here there dawned on me the noti=
on that we must admit, in some sense, a fourth dimension of space for the p=
urpose of calculating with triples ... An electric circuit seemed to close,=
 and a spark flashed forth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-letter1843_1-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-lette=
r1843-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> </p></blockquote>
<p>Hamilton called a quadruple with these rules of multiplication a <i>quat=
ernion</i>, and he devoted most of the remainder of his life to studying an=
d teaching them. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_Hamilto=
nian_quaternions" title=3D"Classical Hamiltonian quaternions">Hamilton's tr=
eatment</a> is more <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" titl=
e=3D"Geometry">geometric</a> than the modern approach, which emphasizes qua=
ternions' <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebr=
a">algebraic</a> properties. He founded a school of "quaternionists", and h=
e tried to popularize quaternions in several books. The last and longest of=
 his books, <i>Elements of Quaternions</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HamiltonElem=
ents_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qua=
ternion#cite_note-HamiltonElements-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> was 800&nbsp;pages long;=
 it was edited by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Edwin_Ha=
milton" title=3D"William Edwin Hamilton">his son</a> and published shortly =
after his death.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikip=
edia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"Th=
is claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2025)">citation n=
eeded</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>After Hamilton's death, the Scottish mathematical physicist <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Guthrie_Tait" title=3D"Peter Guthri=
e Tait">Peter Tait</a> became the chief exponent of quaternions. At this ti=
me, quaternions were a mandatory examination topic in Dublin. Topics in phy=
sics and geometry that would now be described using vectors, such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinematics" title=3D"Kinematics">kinemat=
ics</a> in space and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell%27s_e=
quations" title=3D"Maxwell's equations">Maxwell's equations</a>, were descr=
ibed entirely in terms of quaternions. There was even a professional resear=
ch association, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion_Ass=
ociation" title=3D"Quaternion Association">Quaternion Association</a>, devo=
ted to the study of quaternions and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Hypercomplex_number" title=3D"Hypercomplex number">hypercomplex num=
ber</a> systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>From the mid-1880s, quaternions began to be displaced by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Vector analysis">vector analysis</a>, which had been developed by <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josiah_Willard_Gibbs" title=3D"Josiah W=
illard Gibbs">Josiah Willard Gibbs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Oliver_Heaviside" title=3D"Oliver Heaviside">Oliver Heaviside</a>, an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_von_Helmholtz" title=3D"=
Hermann von Helmholtz">Hermann von Helmholtz</a>. Vector analysis described=
 the same phenomena as quaternions, so it borrowed some ideas and terminolo=
gy liberally from the literature on quaternions. However, vector analysis w=
as conceptually simpler and notationally cleaner, and eventually quaternion=
s were relegated to a minor role in mathematics and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>. A side-effect of =
this transition is that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_=
Hamiltonian_quaternions" title=3D"Classical Hamiltonian quaternions">Hamilt=
on's work</a> is difficult to comprehend for many modern readers. Hamilton'=
s original definitions are unfamiliar and his writing style was wordy and d=
ifficult to follow.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" sty=
le=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wik=
ipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"=
This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2025)">citation=
 needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>However, quaternions have had a revival since the late 20th&nbsp;cen=
tury, primarily due to their utility in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Quaternions_and_spatial_rotation" title=3D"Quaternions and spatial ro=
tation">describing spatial rotations</a>. The representations of rotations =
by quaternions are more compact and quicker to compute than the representat=
ions by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" titl=
e=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>. In addition, unlike Euler angles, =
they are not susceptible to "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimba=
l_lock" title=3D"Gimbal lock">gimbal lock</a>". For this reason, quaternion=
s are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_graphics" t=
itle=3D"Computer graphics">computer graphics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Shoema=
ke_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quate=
rnion#cite_note-Shoemake-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-19">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_vision" title=
=3D"Computer vision">computer vision</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Robotics" title=3D"Robotics">robotics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite=
_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_magn=
etic_resonance" title=3D"Nuclear magnetic resonance">nuclear magnetic reson=
ance</a> image sampling,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mamone_6-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-Mamone-6"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_theory" title=3D"=
Control theory">control theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Signal_processing" title=3D"Signal processing">signal processing</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spacecraft_attitude_control" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spacecraft attitude control">attitude control</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physics<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics" title=3D"Bioi=
nformatics">bioinformatics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
lecular_dynamics" title=3D"Molecular dynamics">molecular dynamics</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_simulation" title=3D"Computer=
 simulation">computer simulations</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Orbital_mechanics" title=3D"Orbital mechanics">orbital mechanics</=
a>. For example, it is common for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Spacecraft_attitude_control" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spacecraft =
attitude control">attitude control</a> systems of spacecraft to be commande=
d in terms of quaternions. Quaternions also have contributed to <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number=
 theory</a>, because of their relationships with the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_form" title=3D"Quadratic form">quadratic forms=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Quaternions_in_physics">Qua=
ternions in physics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DQuaternion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section=
: Quaternions in physics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Hamilton had introduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biquate=
rnion" title=3D"Biquaternion">biquaternions</a> in his <i>Lectures on Quate=
rnions</i>, and these were used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Ludwik_Silberstein" title=3D"Ludwik Silberstein">Ludwik Silberstein</a> in=
 1914 to exhibit the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_trans=
formation" title=3D"Lorentz transformation">Lorentz transformations</a> of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Speci=
al relativity">special relativity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-22"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> This representation of Lorentz transformations was also used by <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornelius_Lanczos" title=3D"Corneli=
us Lanczos">Cornelius Lanczos</a> in 1949.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-23=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>The finding of 1924 that in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a> the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_(physics)" title=3D"Spin (phys=
ics)">spin</a> of an electron and other matter particles (known as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinors" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"S=
pinors">spinors</a>) can be described using quaternions (in the form of the=
 famous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pauli_matrices" title=3D"P=
auli matrices">Pauli spin matrices</a>) furthered their interest; quaternio=
ns helped to understand how rotations of electrons by 360=C2=B0 can be disc=
erned from those by 720=C2=B0 (the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Plate_trick" title=3D"Plate trick">Plate trick</a>").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion=
#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-25"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As=
 of 2018<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style=
=3D"display:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DQuaternion&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</a></sup>, t=
heir use has not yet overtaken <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ort=
hogonal_group" title=3D"Orthogonal group">rotation groups</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qua=
ternion#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W._K._Clifford" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"W. K. Clifford">W. K. Clifford</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-r=
ef_cfifford_1878_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-ref_cfifford_1878-28"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (1845 =E2=
=88=92 1879) introduced his algebras as a tensor product (=E2=80=9Dcompound=
 of algebras=E2=80=9D) of quaternion algebras (and its even sub-algebra), a=
 concept introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Pe=
irce" title=3D"Benjamin Peirce">B. Peirce</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_not=
e-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> (1809 =E2=88=92 1880). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/R._Lipschitz" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R. Lipschitz">R. Lipsch=
itz</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (1832 =E2=88=92 1903)=
 rediscovered independently the even subalgebra. In 1922, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarence_Lemuel_Elisha_Moore" title=3D"Clarence Lem=
uel Elisha Moore">C. L. E. Moore</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-31"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> (1876 =E2=88=92 1931) was to call <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Rudolf_Lipschitz" title=3D"Rudolf Lipschitz">Lipschitz</a>=E2=80=99=
 algebras =E2=80=9Dhyperquaternions=E2=80=9D. The term =E2=80=9Dhyperquater=
nion=E2=80=9D designates nowadays both the tensor product of <span class=3D=
"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-i=
nline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://=
www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle n}">
