<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Center">Center</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuaternion&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Center"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_(ring_theory)" title=
=3D"Center (ring theory)"><i>center</i></a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Noncommutative_ring" title=3D"Noncommutative ring">noncommut=
ative ring</a> is the subring of elements <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>cx</=
i> =3D <i>xc</i></span> for every <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">x</span>. The center of the quaternion algebra is the subf=
ield of scalar quaternions. In fact, it is a part of the definition that th=
e scalar quaternions belong to the center. Conversely, if <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>q</i> =3D <i>a</i> + <i>b</i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d=
</i> <b>k</b></span> belongs to the center, then
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle 0=3D\mathbf {i} \,q-q\,\mathbf {i} =3D2c\,\mathbf {ij} +2d\,\ma=
thbf {ik} =3D2c\,\mathbf {k} -2d\,\mathbf {j} ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>0</mn>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">i</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">i</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">i</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">j</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">i</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">k</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">k</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">j</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 0=3D\mathbf {=
i} \,q-q\,\mathbf {i} =3D2c\,\mathbf {ij} +2d\,\mathbf {ik} =3D2c\,\mathbf =
{k} -2d\,\mathbf {j} ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/fd108c7242311c4bc42466350d341f446effd678" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.671ex; width:40.606ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 0=
=3D\mathbf {i} \,q-q\,\mathbf {i} =3D2c\,\mathbf {ij} +2d\,\mathbf {ik} =3D=
2c\,\mathbf {k} -2d\,\mathbf {j} ,}"></span>
</p><p>and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>c</i> =3D <i>d</i> =3D 0</span>. A si=
milar computation with <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>j</b></span> instead of <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><b>i</b></span> shows that one has also <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> =3D 0</span>. Thus <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>q</i> =
=3D <i>a</i></span> is a scalar quaternion.
</p><p>The quaternions form a division algebra. This means that the non-com=
mutativity of multiplication is the only property that makes quaternions di=
fferent from a field. This non-commutativity has some unexpected consequenc=
es, among them that a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_e=
quation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial equation">polynomial equ=
ation</a> over the quaternions can have more distinct solutions than the de=
gree of the polynomial. For example, the equation <span class=3D"nowrap"><s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>z</i><sup>2</sup> + 1 =3D 0</span>,</span> has inf=
initely many quaternion solutions, which are the quaternions <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>z</i> =3D <i>b</i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d</i> <b>=
k</b></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>c<=
/i><sup>2</sup> + <i>d</i><sup>2</sup> =3D 1</span>. Thus these <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_unit" title=3D"Imaginary unit">imag=
inary units</a> form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_sphere=
" title=3D"Unit sphere">unit sphere</a> in the three-dimensional space of q=
uaternion vectors.
</p>
