on: Scalar and vector parts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A quaternion of the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> + 0 <b>i</b> +=
 0 <b>j</b> + 0 <b>k</b></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> is a real number, is called a <i>scalar qu=
aternion</i> (sometimes <i>real quaternion</i>), and a quaternion of the fo=
rm <span class=3D"texhtml">0 + <i>b</i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d=
</i> <b>k</b></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">b</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">c</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>d</span> are real numbers, and at least one of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">d</span> is nonzero, is called a <i>vector quaternion</=
i> (sometimes <i>right quaternion</i>. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =
+ <i>b</i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d</i> <b>k</b></span> is any q=
uaternion, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a=
</span> is called its <i>scalar part</i> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</=
i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d</i> <b>k</b></span> is called its <i=
>vector part</i>. Even though every quaternion can be viewed as a vector in=
 a four-dimensional vector space, it is common to refer to the vector part =
as vectors in three-dimensional space. With this convention, a vector is th=
e same as an element of the vector space <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mw=
e-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathm=
l-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math=
/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbb {R} ^{3}.}">
  <semantics>
