ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-49"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</li>
<li>The scalar part of a quaternion is one half of the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_trace" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix tr=
ace">matrix trace</a>.</li>
<li>The conjugate of a quaternion corresponds to the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugate_transpose" title=3D"Conjugate transpose">conju=
gate transpose</a> of the matrix.</li>
<li>By restriction this representation yields a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Group_isomorphism" title=3D"Group isomorphism">group isomorph=
ism</a> between the subgroup of unit quaternions and their image <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SU(2)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SU(2)"=
>SU(2)</a>. Topologically, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uni=
t_quaternion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unit quaternion">unit quaterni=
ons</a> are the 3-sphere, so the underlying space of SU(2) is also a 3-sphe=
re. The group <span class=3D"texhtml">SU(2)</span> is important for describ=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_(physics)" title=3D"Spin =
(physics)">spin</a> in quantum mechanics; see <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Pauli_matrices" title=3D"Pauli matrices">Pauli matrices</a>.</l=
i>
<li>There is a strong relation between quaternions and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pauli_matrices" title=3D"Pauli matrices">Pauli matrice=
