<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Lagrange's_four-square_theo=
rem"><span id=3D"Lagrange.27s_four-square_theorem"></span>Lagrange's four-s=
quare theorem</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DQuaternion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: La=
grange's four-square theorem"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange%27s_four-sq=
uare_theorem" title=3D"Lagrange's four-square theorem">Lagrange's four-squa=
re theorem</a></div>
<p>Quaternions are also used in one of the proofs of Lagrange's four-square=
 theorem in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=
=3D"Number theory">number theory</a>, which states that every nonnegative i=
nteger is the sum of four integer squares. As well as being an elegant theo=
rem in its own right, Lagrange's four square theorem has useful application=
s in areas of mathematics outside number theory, such as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorial_design" title=3D"Combinatorial design"=
>combinatorial design</a> theory. The quaternion-based proof uses <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurwitz_quaternion" title=3D"Hurwitz quat=
ernion">Hurwitz quaternions</a>, a subring of the ring of all quaternions f=
or which there is an analog of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Euclidean_algorithm" title=3D"Euclidean algorithm">Euclidean algorithm</a>=
.
</p>
