<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Three-dimensional_and_four-=
dimensional_rotation_groups">Three-dimensional and four-dimensional rotatio=
n groups</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQua=
ternion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Three-di=
mensional and four-dimensional rotation groups"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternions_and_spa=
tial_rotation" title=3D"Quaternions and spatial rotation">Quaternions and s=
patial rotation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_o=
perator_(vector_space)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rotation operator (v=
ector space)">Rotation operator (vector space)</a></div>
<p>The word "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugation_(group_th=
eory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Conjugation (group theory)">conjugati=
on</a>", besides the meaning given above, can also mean taking an element <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> to <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>r=E2=80=AFa=E2=80=AFr</i><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> =
where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> is=
 some nonzero quaternion. All <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conj=
ugacy_class" title=3D"Conjugacy class">elements that are conjugate to a giv=
en element</a> (in this sense of the word conjugate) have the same real par=
t and the same norm of the vector part. (Thus the conjugate in the other se=
nse is one of the conjugates in this sense.)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_not=
e-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Thus the multiplicative group of nonzero quaternions acts by conjuga=
tion on the copy of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline=
"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"disp=
lay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{=
\displaystyle \mathbb {R} ^{3}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">R</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>3</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbb {R} ^=
{3}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f936ddf584f8f3dd2a0ed08917001b7a404c10b5" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.732ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thbb {R} ^{3}}"></span> consisting of quaternions with real part equal to z=
ero. Conjugation by a unit quaternion (a quaternion of absolute value 1) wi=
th real part <span class=3D"texhtml">cos(<i>=CF=86</i>)</span> is a rotatio=
n by an angle <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>=CF=86</i></span>, the axis of th=
e rotation being the direction of the vector part. The advantages of quater=
nions are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Avoiding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gimbal_lock" titl=
e=3D"Gimbal lock">gimbal lock</a>, a problem with systems such as Euler ang=
les.</li>
<li>Faster and more compact than matrices.</li>
<li>Nonsingular representation (compared with Euler angles for example).</l=
i>
<li>Pairs of unit quaternions represent a rotation in <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-dimensional_space" title=3D"Four-dimensional space=
">4D</a> space (see <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotations_i=
n_4-dimensional_Euclidean_space#Algebra_of_4D_rotations" title=3D"Rotations=
 in 4-dimensional Euclidean space">Rotations in 4-dimensional Euclidean spa=
ce: Algebra of 4D&nbsp;rotations</a></i>).</li></ul>
<p>The set of all unit quaternions (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Versor" title=3D"Versor">versors</a>) forms a 3-sphere <span class=3D"tex=
html"><i>S</i><sup>3</sup></span> and a group (a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Lie_group" title=3D"Lie group">Lie group</a>) under multipli=
cation, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covering_space#Properties"=
 title=3D"Covering space">double covering</a> the group <span class=3D"mwe-=
math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline=
 mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w=
3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\text{SO}}(3,\mathbb {R}=
 )}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mtext>SO</mtext>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mn>3</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">R</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{SO}}(3=
,\mathbb {R} )}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/83f067485af5efb7fd272a8ea6467a6660d85951" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:8.784ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\t=
ext{SO}}(3,\mathbb {R} )}"></span> of real orthogonal 3=C3=973&nbsp;<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_matrix" title=3D"Orthogonal ma=
trix">matrices</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant"=
 title=3D"Determinant">determinant</a>&nbsp;1 since <i>two</i> unit quatern=
ions correspond to every rotation under the above correspondence. See <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plate_trick" title=3D"Plate trick">plat=
e trick</a>.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_groups_=
in_three_dimensions" title=3D"Point groups in three dimensions">Point group=
s in three dimensions</a></div>
<p>The image of a subgroup of versors is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Point_groups_in_three_dimensions" title=3D"Point groups in three d=
imensions">point group</a>, and conversely, the preimage of a point group i=
s a subgroup of versors. The preimage of a finite point group is called by =
the same name, with the prefix <b>binary</b>. For instance, the preimage of=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedral_group" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Icosahedral group">icosahedral group</a> is the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_icosahedral_group" title=3D"Binar=
y icosahedral group">binary icosahedral group</a>.
</p><p>The versors' group is isomorphic to <span class=3D"texhtml">SU(2)</s=
pan>, the group of complex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unitary=
_matrix" title=3D"Unitary matrix">unitary</a> 2=C3=972&nbsp;matrices of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">de=
terminant</a> 1.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurwitz_quate=
rnion" title=3D"Hurwitz quaternion">Hurwitz quaternion</a></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> b=
e the set of quaternions of the form <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>a</i> + <i>b</i> <b>i</b> + <i>c</i> <b>j</b> + <i>d</i> <b>k</=
b></span> </span> where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">a, b, c,</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">d</span> are either all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Integer" title=3D"Integer">integers</a> or all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Half-integer" title=3D"Half-integer">half-integers</a>. The se=
t <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is a r=
ing (in fact a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_(ring_theory=
)" title=3D"Domain (ring theory)">domain</a>) and a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Lattice_(group)" title=3D"Lattice (group)">lattice</a> an=
d is called the ring of Hurwitz quaternions. There are 24 unit quaternions =
in this ring, and they are the vertices of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/24-cell" title=3D"24-cell">regular 24 cell</a> with <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schl%C3%A4fli_symbol" title=3D"Schl=C3=A4fli s=
ymbol">Schl=C3=A4fli symbol</a> <span class=3D"texhtml">{3,4,3}.</span> The=
y correspond to the double cover of the rotational symmetry group of the re=
gular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron" title=3D"Tetrah=
edron">tetrahedron</a>. Similarly, the vertices of a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/600-cell" title=3D"600-cell">regular 600 cell</a> with S=
chl=C3=A4fli symbol <span class=3D"texhtml">{3,3,5</span>} can be taken as =
the unit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosian" title=3D"Icosian=
">icosians</a>, corresponding to the double cover of the rotational symmetr=
y group of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron=
" title=3D"Regular icosahedron">regular icosahedron</a>. The double cover o=
f the rotational symmetry group of the regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Octahedron" title=3D"Octahedron">octahedron</a> corresponds to=
 the quaternions that represent the vertices of the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Disphenoidal_288-cell" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dis=
phenoidal 288-cell">disphenoidal 288-cell</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_not=
e-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Quaternion_algebras">Quater=
nion algebras</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DQuaternion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Qu=
aternion algebras"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion_algebra" =
title=3D"Quaternion algebra">Quaternion algebra</a></div>
<p>The Quaternions can be generalized into further algebras called <i>quate=
rnion algebras</i>. Take <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">F</span> to be any field with characteristic different from 2, and =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> to be elemen=
ts of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span>; a=
 four-dimensional unitary associative algebra can be defined over <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> with basis <span =
class=3D"texhtml"> 1, <b>i</b>, <b>j</b>,</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><b>i j</b></span>, where <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>i</b><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>a</i></span></span>, <span class=3D"nowrap"><spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>j</b><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>b</i></span></span> and <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><b>i j</b> =3D =E2=88=92<b>j i<=
/b></span></span> (so <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><b>(i =
j)</b><sup>2</sup> =3D =E2=88=92<i>a b</i></span></span>).
</p><p>Quaternion algebras are isomorphic to the algebra of 2=C3=972 matric=
es over <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">F</span> =
or form division algebras over <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">F</span>, depending on the choice of <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>.
</p>
