</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/acd427d3aafa49899a7d4c5884bacce3414992f6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:8.793ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \op=
eratorname {Cl} _{4,0}(\mathbb {R} ),}"></span> there are six bivector basi=
s elements, since with four different basic vector directions, six differen=
t pairs and therefore six different linearly independent planes can be defi=
ned. Rotations in such spaces using these generalisations of quaternions, c=
alled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotor_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Rotor (mathematics)">rotors</a>, can be very useful for applications in=
volving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinates" t=
itle=3D"Homogeneous coordinates">homogeneous coordinates</a>. But it is onl=
y in 3D that the number of basis bivectors equals the number of basis vecto=
rs, and each bivector can be identified as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Pseudovector" title=3D"Pseudovector">pseudovector</a>.
</p><p>There are several advantages for placing quaternions in this wider s=
etting:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Rotors are a natural part of geometric algebra and easily understoo=
d as the encoding of a double reflection.</li>
<li>In geometric algebra, a rotor and the objects it acts on live in the sa=
me space. This eliminates the need to change representations and to encode =
new data structures and methods, which is traditionally required when augme=
nting linear algebra with quaternions.</li>
<li>Rotors are universally applicable to any element of the algebra, not ju=
st vectors and other quaternions, but also lines, planes, circles, spheres,=
 rays, and so on.</li>
<li>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conformal_geometric_alg=
ebra" title=3D"Conformal geometric algebra">conformal model</a> of Euclidea=
n geometry, rotors allow the encoding of rotation, translation and scaling =
in a single element of the algebra, universally acting on any element. In p=
articular, this means that rotors can represent rotations around an arbitra=
ry axis, whereas quaternions are limited to an axis through the origin.</li=
>
<li>Rotor-encoded transformations make interpolation particularly straightf=
orward.</li>
<li>Rotors carry over naturally to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Pseudo-Euclidean_space" title=3D"Pseudo-Euclidean space">pseudo-Euclidean =
spaces</a>, for example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minko=
wski_space" title=3D"Minkowski space">Minkowski space</a> of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" title=3D"Special relativity"=
>special relativity</a>. In such spaces rotors can be used to efficiently r=
epresent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorentz_boost" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Lorentz boost">Lorentz boosts</a>, and to interpret fo=
rmulas involving the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_matrice=
s" title=3D"Gamma matrices">gamma matrices</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cita=
tion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources=
. (October 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></li></ul>
<p>For further detail about the geometrical uses of Clifford algebras, see =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_algebra" title=3D"Geomet=
ric algebra">Geometric algebra</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Brauer_group">Brauer group<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuaternion&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Brauer group"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brauer_group"=
 title=3D"Brauer group">Brauer group</a></div>
<p>The quaternions are "essentially" the only (non-trivial) <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_simple_algebra" title=3D"Central simple a=
lgebra">central simple algebra</a> (CSA) over the real numbers, in the sens=
e that every CSA over the real numbers is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Brauer_equivalent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Brauer equivalent=
">Brauer equivalent</a> to either the real numbers or the quaternions. Expl=
icitly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brauer_group" title=3D=
"Brauer group">Brauer group</a> of the real numbers consists of two classes=
, represented by the real numbers and the quaternions, where the Brauer gro=
up is the set of all CSAs, up to equivalence relation of one CSA being a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_ring" title=3D"Matrix ring">m=
atrix ring</a> over another. By the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Artin%E2%80%93Wedderburn_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Artin=E2=
=80=93Wedderburn theorem">Artin=E2=80=93Wedderburn theorem</a> (specificall=
y, Wedderburn's part), CSAs are all matrix algebras over a division algebra=
, and thus the quaternions are the only non-trivial division algebra over t=
he real numbers.
</p><p>CSAs =E2=80=93 finite dimensional rings over a field, which are <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_algebra" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Simple algebra">simple algebras</a> (have no non-trivial 2-sided i=
deals, just as with fields) whose center is exactly the field =E2=80=93 are=
 a noncommutative analog of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extens=
ion_field" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Extension field">extension fields=
</a>, and are more restrictive than general ring extensions. The fact that =
the quaternions are the only non-trivial CSA over the real numbers (up to e=
quivalence) may be compared with the fact that the complex numbers are the =
only non-trivial finite field extension of the real numbers.
</p>
